references: Limited Utility. The missing neighbor generator in FedSage can only recover 1-hop missing neighbors and does not further propagate their features to other neighboring nodes. As illustrated in Fig. 1 (e), for predictions where neighbors further than 1 hop away are important, the model will fail. Such limitation is verified by the limited performance gain of FedSage+ over vanilla FedSage without neighbor generator in [49] as well as our empirical results in Table 2.

We conduct comprehensive ablation experiments to verify the significant elevations brought by our proposed techniques, as shown in TableÂ 2.
The most exciting observation is that besides outperforming local models by an average of 27.13%, FedDEP distinctly elevates the performance of FedGNN by at most 2.13%, and FedSage by at most 3.84%, even by requiring zero communication during the FL of the generators. Notably, similar to FedSage, FedDEP exhibits its capacities in elevating beyond the global classifier which is supposed to provide the performance upper bound, possibly due to the additional model robustness brought by the missing neighbor generators. As shown in the results of CiteSeer in TableÂ 2, FedDEP even excels the global model by at most 2.99%.

references: Privacy-preserving learning over graph data has been widely studied. Differential Privacy (DP)Â

is a widely applied privacy concept in this field, which describes the privacy of a method in protecting individual samples while preserving the analytical properties of the entire dataset.
A prevalent approach in attaining a graph mining model with general DP is DPSGDÂ
, which injects designed noise into clipped gradients during model training. For centralized training scenarios, DPGGANÂ

incorporates DPSGD to achieve DP for individual links on original graphs.
In FL systems, VFGNNÂ
and FedGNNÂ

leverage DPSGD and cryptology techniques to obtain rigorous privacy guarantees for federated graph learning. Meanwhile, to achieve general DP on graphs, there are some other noised-injecting based methods. Previous works of centralized learning Â
, FKGEÂ
and FedGSLÂ
for FL systems, guarantee their proposed techniques with general DP by applying noise perturbation.

However, general DP does not depict the protections for sensitive node features, edges, or neighborhoods, on distributed graphs. Edge local DP and node local DP (edge-LDP and node-LDP) are two specific types of DP targeting local nodesâ€™ neighbor listsÂ
. These novel DP definitions better fit the graph learning that learns from multiple neighbor lists, and match the privacy goal of protecting nodesâ€™ local neighborhoods.
As illustrated in Definition 2.2 inÂ

, edge-LDP defines how much a model tells for two neighborhoods that differ by one edge, while node-LDP promises a modelâ€™s max leakage for all possible neighborhoods. In contrast to node-LDP, which is much stronger and can severely hinder the graph modelâ€™s utility, edge-LDP precisely illustrates the local DP for local neighborhoods without overly constraining the model.
There are several works analyzing edge-LDP over distributed graph data. Qin et al.Â
propose a decentralized social graphs generation technique with the edge-LDP. Imola et al.Â
analyze the edge-LDP of the proposed shuffle techniques in handling the triangle and 4-cycle counting for neighbor lists of distributed users. Lin et al.Â

propose Solitude, an edge-LDP collaborative training framework for distributed graphs, where each client shares its perturbed local graph for the training. However, different from our subgraph FL setting, its central server (data curator) has access to node identities and labels. To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to leverage edge-LDP in the FL setting.
